<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="268" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,391]" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,335,152,176]" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">Etymology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[348,577,152,176]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Bregmosina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obunca">
<emphasis box="[348,577,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">Bregmosina obunca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is named for the hooked surstylus (from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[1204,1297,152,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">obuncus</emphasis>
, bent in or hooked).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="8" pageNumber="268" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,151,391]" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[201,337,223,248]" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[344,567,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Bregmosina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obunca">
<emphasis box="[344,567,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">Bregmosina obunca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[622,748,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Bregmosina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="howdeni">
<emphasis box="[622,748,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">B. howdeni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are obviously closely related but 
<taxonomicName box="[1126,1240,224,248]" class="Insecta" family="Sphaeroceridae" genus="Bregmosina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="268" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="obunca">
<emphasis box="[1126,1240,224,248]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">B. obunca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is distinct for the long, pointed anteroventral surstylus apex and the bilobed posterior margin of male sternite 
<number box="[1194,1211,260,284]" pageId="8" pageNumber="268" value="4.0">4</number>
. Both species differ from congeners by their greatly reduced lower orbital bristle and by the strikingly large posterolateral processes of the male fifth sternite. The 
<typeStatus box="[469,567,332,356]" pageId="8" pageNumber="268">holotype</typeStatus>
was collected at the same time and place as B. buck, but these species are extremely different in male and female abdominal characters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
